<body>
    <h1>Task 17 -Technical Document</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h1 local-id=3D"5b0b1e76b191" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-1.INTR=
ODUCTION">1. INTRODUCTION</h1>
<h2 local-id=3D"6f29f458d602" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-1.1Purpose">1.=
1 Purpose</h2>
<p local-id=3D"65117ddf632d">This document provides a comprehensive technic=
al reference for the design and implementation of a Multi-VPC AWS Network E=
nvironment.<br>
It is intended for the following audience:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"a0437059f80a">
<li local-id=3D"0eae34db2c4f">
<p local-id=3D"4b65102e444f">CTO: High-level architectural decisions, cost,=
 and risk overview</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"7df6cb12fcfb">
<p local-id=3D"4b7c61d05305">Developers: Network boundaries, instance acces=
s, and environment structure</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a307e6788f2b">
<p local-id=3D"09a9ca1f9634">Solution Architects: Infrastructure design, CI=
DR planning, and peering topology</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a7b5963a97bc">
<p local-id=3D"b4ccd694f6bd">DevOps Engineers: Provisioning, routing, autom=
ation, and connectivity validation</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"fa1925ef850e">
<p local-id=3D"02ef90e4c598">Resellers: Understanding of the delivered solu=
tion for client-facing communication</p></li>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"0f4718f525dd">
<h2 local-id=3D"6f2bbe20ad5a" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-1.2Scope">1.2 =
Scope</h2>
<p local-id=3D"bceb68e0fa15">This document covers the complete implementati=
on of a multi-VPC network architecture on Amazon Web Services spanning two =
regions. Specifically, it includes:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"116b84c8bfe4">
<li local-id=3D"354fc52364b1">
<p local-id=3D"da6e0709504c">VPC design and CIDR allocation across us-east-=
1 and us-east-2</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"70ef0e0e9396">
<p local-id=3D"f6edc6370653">Public and private subnet segmentation per env=
ironment</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"ebb39bed2bac">
<p local-id=3D"15d3193eaaf7">Internet Gateway and Route Table configuration=
</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"9e3a7cec1532">
<p local-id=3D"c7b94283cd8c">Cross-region and intra-region VPC Peering setu=
p</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"7413c94bd5fc">
<p local-id=3D"709472dd22b1">EC2 instance deployment for validation purpose=
s</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"9b0593a0ca65">
<p local-id=3D"c8b3af91e4d3">Security group configuration and access contro=
l</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"2635276efdac">
<p local-id=3D"a996ffd318a9">Connectivity testing including success and con=
trolled failure scenarios</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"f468f5a0c687">
<p local-id=3D"f332adf8c8b5">Automation via Python boto3 scripting (bonus d=
eliverable)</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"b675ccdc33bb">This document does not cover application-layer=
 deployments, CI/CD pipelines, or database configurations.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"02bfcd37c7a0">
<h1 local-id=3D"42de69719249" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-2.OVERVIEWOFTH=
EPROJECT">2. OVERVIEW OF THE PROJECT</h1>
<h2 local-id=3D"d019df383f6d" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-2.1Definition"=
>2.1 Definition</h2>
<p local-id=3D"773a11ab19d3">A Multi-VPC AWS network environment is an infr=
astructure pattern in which multiple isolated Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs)=
 are deployed within or across AWS regions, each representing a distinct ne=
twork boundary. VPC Peering is used to establish controlled, private connec=
tivity between selected VPC pairs without traffic traversing the public int=
ernet.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f72dc52657ad">This approach is widely adopted in enterprise =
cloud deployments where teams, departments, or geographic offices require n=
etwork isolation with selective inter-connectivity. Benefits include improv=
ed security posture, reduced blast radius in the event of a breach, simplif=
ied compliance enforcement, and granular traffic control via route tables a=
nd security groups.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"701314e7d790">
<h2 local-id=3D"08f2be8f3fdc" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-2.2KeyPrincipl=
es=E2=80=94AWSWell-ArchitectedFramework">2.2 Key Principles =E2=80=94 AWS W=
ell-Architected Framework</h2>
<p local-id=3D"bdbfe3612a1c"><strong>OPERATIONAL EXCELLENCE</strong><br>
Achieved through infrastructure-as-code (boto3 automation script) enabling =
repeatable, consistent provisioning and reducing manual error.</p>
<p local-id=3D"9a66ec1f514b"><strong>SECURITY</strong><br>
Achieved through VPC isolation, private subnet segregation, least-privilege=
 security groups, and restricting all inter-VPC traffic to explicitly peere=
d connections only.</p>
<p local-id=3D"24be9ea5d4ce"><strong>RELIABILITY</strong><br>
Achieved through non-overlapping CIDR planning to prevent routing conflicts=
, and by distributing environments across two AWS regions for logical redun=
dancy.</p>
<p local-id=3D"685d363e02ee"><strong>PERFORMANCE EFFICIENCY</strong><br>
Achieved through right-sized /16 VPCs allowing future horizontal scaling, a=
nd subnet sizing tailored to each office's capacity requirements.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f62730f4555e"><strong>COST OPTIMISATION</strong><br>
Achieved by using VPC Peering (no Transit Gateway overhead), deploying only=
 the necessary EC2 instances for validation, and leveraging native AWS netw=
orking features where possible.</p>
<p local-id=3D"024727d80b35"><strong>SUSTAINABILITY</strong><br>
Achieved by minimising resource sprawl through structured CIDR planning and=
 automated provisioning that avoids over-provisioning.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"344d2f59b9a2">
<h2 local-id=3D"0c2d920ace7a" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-2.3GoalsandObj=
ectives">2.3 Goals and Objectives</h2>
<p local-id=3D"572bd1a7b125">The primary goals of this implementation were:=
</p>
<ul local-id=3D"37ffbef6227c">
<li local-id=3D"89fc2eee388f">
<p local-id=3D"1abda1ee24e1">Simulate an enterprise-grade AWS network for a=
 client with headquarters and distributed branch offices</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"0220545b2105">
<p local-id=3D"8195e4923500">Establish secure, isolated VPCs for each envir=
onment</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b7d707574a00">
<p local-id=3D"da9a7ca1ed43">Enable controlled communication between HQ and=
 branch offices via VPC Peering</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"d76c553d044d">
<p local-id=3D"4de30409dde1">Validate all connectivity paths through struct=
ured testing</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b7a8903ab69a">
<p local-id=3D"f090d8cef1e8">Demonstrate controlled traffic blocking for no=
n-peered routes</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"bfa4b314c1fe">
<p local-id=3D"8178b48df9ea">Deliver a reusable automation script for futur=
e provisioning</p></li>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"fb82b52f3d2e">
<h2 local-id=3D"c3dd39a81691" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-2.4Constraints=
andAssumptions">2.4 Constraints and Assumptions</h2>
<p local-id=3D"f1f8cf8d60f8"><strong>Constraints:</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"8a0bfeae4ca2">
<li local-id=3D"ed268248e47c">
<p local-id=3D"3fa735063087">All environments provisioned within the AWS Fr=
ee Tier and minimal paid resource usage</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"60300950f400">
<p local-id=3D"55631de9384e">Connectivity validated using EC2 t2.micro inst=
ances only</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"e9fba04cfb48">
<p local-id=3D"d27014eb7d00">No Transit Gateway used; all routing via VPC P=
eering only</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"bad98464b4ac">
<p local-id=3D"1c3fa9d86f15">No NAT Gateway deployed; private subnets have =
no outbound internet access by design</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"cc6dad753cce"><strong>Assumptions:</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"30db993bdc8a">
<li local-id=3D"e0141aed0971">
<p local-id=3D"7b657cc5904a">VPC Peering is sufficient for current inter-of=
fice communication requirements</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"2b5ef68b0841">
<p local-id=3D"e2df9ea86b70">Each office environment is represented by a si=
ngle VPC</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"37a928cfbe24">
<p local-id=3D"f57ef7c38259">Future workloads will be deployed into existin=
g subnets</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"c3560d53a820">
<p local-id=3D"42e248b56f6a">Security group rules will be tightened further=
 for production workloads</p></li>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"73c948d375db">
<h1 local-id=3D"917bc27bcc98" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-3.ARCHITECTURE=
ANDINFRASTRUCTURE">3. ARCHITECTURE AND INFRASTRUCTURE</h1>
<h2 local-id=3D"9387b4077b17" id=3D"Task17-TechnicalDocument-3.1Infrastruct=
ureOverview">3.1 Infrastructure Overview</h2>
<p local-id=3D"ea7cc0cb17c1">The infrastructure consists of six VPCs distri=
buted across two AWS regions. Two VPCs represent Headquarters environments =
in us-east-1 (N. Virginia), and four VPCs represent branch offices in us-ea=
st-2 (Ohio). Each VPC is fully isolated at the network level with dedicated=
 subnets, Internet Gateways, and route tables.</p>
<p local-id=3D"812c960852a0">Inter-VPC communication is established exclusi=
vely through AWS VPC Peering connections. Seven peering connections in tota=
l were configured =E2=80=94 four cross-region and three intra-region =E2=80=
=94 creating a hub-and-spoke style topology where HQ VPCs connect to their =
respective offices, with additional peering between co-located environments=
.</p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper image-center-wrapper c=
onfluence-embedded-manual-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image ima=
ge-center" alt=3D"image (14)-20260322-144010.png" width=3D"468" loading=3D"=
lazy" src=3D"93e1202b15bf68921ae5f520524b7ba2c3f9f58441667b20a6cb831b8ebf6c=
e9" data-image-src=3D"https://iamops.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachment=
s/1887305829/image%20(14)-20260322-144010.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationD=
ate=3D1774190457928&amp;cacheVersion=3D1&amp;api=3Dv2" data-height=3D"1173"=
 data-width=3D"5891" data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-linked-resour=
ce-id=3D"1887305915" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resourc=
e-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image (14)-2026=
0322-144010.png" data-base-url=3D"https://iamops.atlassian.net/wiki" data-l=
inked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-container-id=
